{
    text = text.ToUpper(); // Only modifies the local copy — original is unchanged
}
```

The variable `text` is local to the method. Reassigning it does **not** affect `message` in `Main`.

---

## The Fix

Use the **`ref` keyword** to pass the string by reference, allowing the method to modify the original variable.

---

## Corrected Code

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void ChangeString(ref string text)
    {
        text = text.ToUpper();
    }

    static void Main()
    {
        string message = "hello";
        ChangeString(ref message); // ref required at call site too
        Console.WriteLine(message); // Output: HELLO
    }
}
```

---

## Alternative: Return the Value (Preferred)

Using `ref` is valid, but **returning the value** is generally cleaner and more idiomatic in C#:

```csharp
static string ChangeString(string text)
{
    return text.ToUpper();
}

static void Main()
{
    string message = "hello";
    message = ChangeString(message);
    Console.WriteLine(message); // Output: HELLO
}
```

> ✅ Prefer the **return approach** — it avoids side effects and is easier to read and test.

