Question:
I am getting a NullReferenceException when trying to access an object.

Code:
using System;

class Person
{
public string Name;
}

class Program
{
static void Main()
{
Person p = null;
Console.WriteLine(p.Name);
}
}

Why does this cause a NullReferenceException, and how can I fix it?

answer:
`NullReferenceException` happens because `p` does not point to a real `Person` object.

### What is wrong
In this line:

```csharp
Person p = null;
```

`p` is explicitly set to `null`, which means “no object”.  
So when you do:

```csharp
Console.WriteLine(p.Name);
```

the program tries to access `Name` on a non-existent object, which throws `NullReferenceException`.

### Fix
Create a `Person` instance before accessing its fields.

### Corrected code
```csharp
using System;

class Person
{
    public string Name;
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Person p = new Person();
        p.Name = "Alice";

        Console.WriteLine(p.Name);
    }
}
```

### Summary
- `null` means the variable does not reference an object.
- Accessing members on `null` causes `NullReferenceException`.
- Fix it by initializing the object with `new Person()` before using it.

