Code:
using System;

class Person
{
public int Age;
}

class Program
{
static void UpdateAge(Person p)
{
p = new Person();
p.Age = 30;
}

static void Main()
{
Person person = new Person();
person.Age = 20;

UpdateAge(person);

Console.WriteLine(person.Age);
}
}

Why does the age not change, and how can I fix this?

answer:
`Person` is a **reference type**, but in C# the **reference itself is passed by value** by default.

## What’s happening

In `Main`, `person` points to a `Person` object with `Age = 20`.

When you call:

```csharp
UpdateAge(person);
```

the method gets a **copy of the reference**. Inside `UpdateAge`:

```csharp
p = new Person();
p.Age = 30;
```

you make `p` point to a **new object**, but only the local copy `p` changes. The original `person` in `Main` still points to the old object, so its `Age` stays `20`.

## What is wrong

This line is the problem:

```csharp
p = new Person();
```

It reassigns the local parameter instead of modifying the original object.

## One clear fix

Modify the existing object instead of creating a new one.

## Corrected code

```csharp
using System;

class Person
{
    public int Age;
}

class Program
{
    static void UpdateAge(Person p)
    {
        p.Age = 30;
    }

    static void Main()
    {
        Person person = new Person();
        person.Age = 20;

        UpdateAge(person);

        Console.WriteLine(person.Age); // 30
    }
}
```

If you want changes to be reflected, update the object that was passed in, not the parameter reference itself.

