Question:
After upgrading my Spring Boot application, one of my REST endpoints returns 404 when I call it with a trailing slash.

Code:
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;
import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1")
public class TodosController {

@GetMapping("/locations")
public List<Integer> findAllCoordinates() {
return List.of(10, 15);
}
}

Why can '/api/v1/locations/' return 404 while '/api/v1/locations' works, and how can I fix it?

answer:
`/api/v1/locations/` can return `404` because newer Spring Boot / Spring MVC versions changed how path matching works.

## 1) The problem

Your controller maps this exact path:

```java
@GetMapping("/locations")
```

That matches:

```text
/api/v1/locations
```

But not necessarily:

```text
/api/v1/locations/
```

In older setups, Spring often treated a trailing slash as equivalent. After upgrading, that behavior may no longer be enabled by default, so `/locations` and `/locations/` are treated as different URLs.

## 2) What is wrong

Nothing is wrong with your method itself. The issue is that your mapping only declares `/locations`, while the request you send is `/locations/`.

So after the upgrade, the trailing slash is no longer automatically ignored.

## 3) One clear fix

Make the endpoint explicitly accept both paths.

That is the most direct and practical fix if you want both URLs to work.

## 4) Corrected code

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1")
public class TodosController {

    @GetMapping({"/locations", "/locations/"})
    public List<Integer> findAllCoordinates() {
        return List.of(10, 15);
    }
}
```

Now both of these will work:

- `/api/v1/locations`
- `/api/v1/locations/`

