Question:
After upgrading my Spring Boot application, one of my REST endpoints returns 404 when I call it with a trailing slash.

Code:
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;
import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1")
public class TodosController {

@GetMapping("/locations")
public List<Integer> findAllCoordinates() {
return List.of(10, 15);
}
}

Why can '/api/v1/locations/' return 404 while '/api/v1/locations' works, and how can I fix it?

answer:
## The Problem

Starting with **Spring Boot 2.6+** (and enforced more strictly in **Spring Boot 3.x**), trailing slash matching was **disabled by default**. Previously, Spring MVC would automatically treat `/api/v1/locations` and `/api/v1/locations/` as equivalent. Now they are treated as distinct paths, so the trailing slash version returns 404.

---

## What's Wrong

Your mapping `/locations` only matches `/api/v1/locations`. When a client calls `/api/v1/locations/`, Spring finds no matching handler and returns `404 Not Found`.

---

## The Fix

The recommended solution is to explicitly add the trailing slash variant to your mapping using the `value` array in `@GetMapping` — **no framework config changes needed**, and it works across all Spring Boot versions.

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;
import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1")
public class TodosController {

    @GetMapping({"/locations", "/locations/"})  // explicitly handle both variants
    public List<Integer> findAllCoordinates() {
        return List.of(10, 15);
    }
}
```

---

## Why Not Re-enable Global Trailing Slash Matching?

You *could* re-enable the old behaviour globally via `WebMvcConfigurer`, but **Spring has deprecated this option** and it will be removed in a future release:

```java
// ⚠️ Deprecated — avoid this approach
@Configuration
public class WebConfig implements WebMvcConfigurer {
    @Override
    public void configurePathMatch(PathMatchConfigurer configurer) {
        configurer.setUseTrailingSlashMatch(true); // deprecated
    }
}
```

---

## Summary

| Approach | Works | Recommended |
|---|---|---|
| `@GetMapping({"/locations", "/locations/"})` | ✅ | ✅ Yes |
| Global `setUseTrailingSlashMatch(true)` | ✅ | ❌ Deprecated |

Explicitly declaring both paths is the **clearest, most future-proof** solution.

